\begin_layout Section
Updating the partition fraction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conditionally averaged continuity equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condCont"

\end_inset

), predicts 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the continuity equation for the gases phases predicts 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}\rho_{gis}$
\end_inset

.
 In most of the transport equations, (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condMom"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condTheta"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 appear together and so they are stored as a single variable.
 However in the equation of state, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 appears without 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The equation of state can be used to update 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 given the old value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the new value of the pressure, 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\text{new}}$
\end_inset

, calculated from the Helmholtz equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Helmholtz"

\end_inset

).
 This is done by assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all partitions and equating 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 from the solution of the Helmholtz equation with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 calculated from the perfect gas equation of state in region 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{i}^{\text{new}}=\frac{\sum_{s}(\sigma_{i}\rho_{gis})R_{s}T_{i}}{p(1-v_{\ell i})}.\label{eq:sigma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This allows each partition to have different densities and temperatures
 but to share the same pressure.
 The volume occupied by each partition is adjusted so that the density and
 temperature do not change but the pressures are equalised.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Potential Temperature Averaged over Partitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We would like the equation of state in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 to hold globally (eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condState"

\end_inset

) but also to hold in every partition (eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condStatei"

\end_inset

) with the same Exner pressure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 This requirement informs the method of averaging 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 over partitions, 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta=\frac{\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}R_{ti}\theta_{i}}{\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}R_{ti}}.\label{eq:theta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Heating in 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The thermodynamic variables for each partition 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 as defined in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:progs"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore the transport equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 (eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condTheta"

\end_inset

) contains a source term due to adiabatic expansion and a source term due
 to latent heating, modified from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BF02"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{i}=-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}\left(\frac{R_{ti}}{c_{vti}}-\kappa\frac{c_{pti}}{c_{vti}}\right)+\frac{C_{i}}{c_{vti}}\left[\frac{c_{va}L_{vi}}{c_{pa}T_{i}}-R_{v}\left(1-\kappa\frac{c_{pti}}{R_{ti}}\right)\right].\label{eq:heating}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Constructing the Helmholtz Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Helmholtz equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is constructed from the continuity equation by substituting
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho=\Psi\pi\label{eq:rhoComp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

into the rate of change of density (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 is the compressibility) and by substituting the flux from the momentum
 for each partition into the divergence term of the continuity equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\Psi\pi}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\left(\sum_{i}F_{i}\right)=0.\label{eq:contForPi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The compressibility, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

, is calculated from equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rhoComp"

\end_inset

) after summing the densities in all partitions to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 using the equation in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:diags"

\end_inset

 and using the equation of state (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condState"

\end_inset

) to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 The fluxes, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}$
\end_inset

, are updated using the momentum equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condMom"

\end_inset

) in direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

 and by expressing the pressure gradient in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sigma_{i}\nabla p=\sigma_{i}p_{0}\nabla\pi^{1/\kappa}=\frac{\sigma_{i}p_{0}}{\kappa}\pi^{\frac{1-\kappa}{\kappa}}\nabla\pi & = & \frac{\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}R_{ti}\theta_{i}c_{pa}}{R_{a}(1-v_{\ell i})}\nabla\pi=\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}c_{pa}\theta_{\rho i}\nabla\pi
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the density potential temperature for each partition is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\theta_{\rho i} & = & \frac{R_{ti}\theta_{i}}{R_{a}(1-v_{\ell i})}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The by taking the dot product of the discretised momentum equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condMom"

\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

 we can find the flux at the new time-step, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the pressure gradient and other terms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{i}^{n+1}=F_{i}^{\prime}-\alpha\Delta t\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}c_{pa}\theta_{\rho i}\nabla_{S}\pi^{n+1}\label{eq:newFluxi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla_{S}\pi=\mathbf{S}\cdot\nabla\pi
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

 is the face area vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the off-centering parameter for the time-stepping and the explicit component
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 calculated from the momentum equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condMom"

\end_inset

) without the new value of the pressure gradient term
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{i}^{\prime}=F_{i}^{n}- & (1-\alpha\Delta t) & \left\{ \nabla\cdot\left(\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}\right)+2\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}\boldsymbol{\Omega}\times\mathbf{u}_{i}+\sigma_{i}\nabla p-\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}\mathbf{g}\right\} ^{n}\cdot\mathbf{S}\\
- & \alpha\Delta t & \left\{ \nabla\cdot\left(\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}\right)+2\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}\boldsymbol{\Omega}\times\mathbf{u}_{i}-\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}\mathbf{g}\right\} ^{\ell}\cdot\mathbf{S}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where superscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 specify the time-level and superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 means the most up to date value of time level 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 calculated explicitly.
 This assumes predictor-corrector time-stepping such as multi-stage RK2.
 Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:newFluxi"

\end_inset

) is then substituted into equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:contForPi"

\end_inset

) to create the Helmholtz equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\Psi\pi}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\sum_{i}F_{i}^{\prime}-\alpha\Delta t\nabla\cdot\left(\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}c_{pa}\theta_{\rho i}\right)\nabla_{S}\pi^{n+1}=0.\label{eq:Helmholtz}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 is then substituted back into eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:newFluxi"

\end_inset

) to calculate each 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Spatial Discretisation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A staggered finite volume discretisation is used.
 The velocity at cell faces for each partition is reconstructed from the
 face mass flux and the partition density:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{u}_{i}=\left(\left(\sum_{\text{faces}}\mathbf{S}\mathbf{S}^{T}\right)^{-1}\sum_{\text{faces}}F_{i}\mathbf{S}\right)_{f}\bigg/\left(\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}\right)_{f}\label{eq:reconU}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\right)_{f}$
\end_inset

 means interpolation from cell centre values onto face values and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

 is the face area vector (outward pointing normal to each face with magnitude
 of the face area.
 For a uniform velocity field, this reconstruction formula reproduces exactly
 the definition of the face flux, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}=\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

 given in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:progs"

\end_inset

.
 The summations are over all of the faces of a cell.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A multi-dimensional, method of lines, linear upwind advection scheme is
 used for advecting species concentrations, velocity and potential temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Pressure Gradient Term
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:gradP"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conditionally averaged momentum equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condMom"

\end_inset

) ignores the terms due to sub-filter scale pressure varations described
 in eqns (30-35) of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TWW+1x"

\end_inset

.
 Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:condMom"

\end_inset

) gives the pressure gradient term as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}\nabla p$
\end_inset

.
 This term should actually be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{I_{i}\nabla p}=\sigma_{i}\nabla\overline{p}+\mathbf{b}_{i}+\sum_{j}\mathbf{d}_{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{d}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the force exerted by fluid 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 on fluid 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 (like a form drag).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{d}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 satisfies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{p\nabla I_{i}}=-\sum_{j}\mathbf{d}_{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a further correction defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{b}_{i}=\left(\overline{\nabla(I_{i}p)}-\sigma_{i}\nabla\overline{p}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

I don't know how to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{d}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

 but they appear to be important ...
\end_layout

