 and they do not oscillate from one time-step to another.
 The instability therefore appears not to be a numerical instability but
 rather an instability of the underlying continuous equations.
 The simulations with smaller time-steps have smaller amplitude oscillations
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 but the same instability in the other fields and divergence between the
 partitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a test of the code, a version was set up with no interaction between
 the partitions, a separate pressure for each partition and the same initial
 conditions as described above.
 The stable partition (without the buoyancy perturbation) remained motionless
 for the 1000 seconds of the simulation whereas the buoyant partion evolved
 very similarly to the simulations presented by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BF02"

\end_inset

.
 However this is not a realistic situation - with independent pressures
 for each partition, one partition could become pressurised in comparison
 to the other.
 However identical pressures cannot work either, as will be described in
 the following section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Thought Experiment with a Partitioned Shallow Water Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine the conditionally averaged non-rotating shallow water equations
 with two partitions which share the same geopotential, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\partial\mathbf{u}_{i}}{\partial t}+\mathbf{u}_{i}\cdot\nabla\mathbf{u}_{i} & = & -\nabla\Psi\\
\frac{\partial\sigma_{i}\Psi}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\sigma_{i}\Psi\mathbf{u}_{i} & = & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}+\sigma_{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Consider a square domain with doubly periodic boundary conditions.
 The initial conditions in partition zero consist of a steady vortex with
 a low pressure centre to balance the non-linear advection term.
 Partition one is initially at rest.
 The low pressure will lead to convergence in partition 1 which will fill
 the low pressure which will in turn lead to divergence in partition 0,
 leading to gravity waves in both partitions.
 Since the only coupling between the partitions is through a pressure gradient,
 no rotation can be transferred between the partitions and so the vortex
 in partion one will remain soley in partition one.
 If instead we wished to maintain independent balance in each partition,
 we would need independent geopotentials for each partion and we would need
 another equation in order to make the system well posed.
 
\end_layout

